1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:05,500
As I told you, one time
I was washing my clothes

2
00:00:06,291 --> 00:00:13,125
One of them came in and said, do you think you are
at your family's house? Because I was undressed, pardon me

3
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:16,708
He said, do you think you are at home?
He was one of the guards who treated us badly

4
00:00:17,250 --> 00:00:21,083
Do you think you are at your family's house,
washing your clothes from the smell of smoke

5
00:00:21,791 --> 00:00:28,416
I could not talk back but I said, as you wish sheikh,
I washed them because they started to smell

6
00:00:28,958 --> 00:00:30,750
Because of the disciplinary cell,
they smelled terrible

7
00:00:31,708 --> 00:00:36,625
After that I started paying close attention
to every word they said outside

8
00:00:36,958 --> 00:00:41,250
With every sound, every sound of a prisoner
being beaten, and every person screaming

9
00:00:41,916 --> 00:00:48,125
The one who cries out, oh God,
and the guard responds, now you know God, now you have returned

10
00:00:48,625 --> 00:00:54,666
Interviewer: Was there any way to talk when you were
in the solitary cells next to each other? Could you communicate?

11
00:00:54,791 --> 00:01:02,375
It is true the solitary cells are adjacent,
but it was impossible to communicate, we only heard the call to prayer

12
00:01:02,875 --> 00:01:05,958
We only heard the call to prayer,
and the <i>muaazin</i> was one of the prisoners

13
00:01:06,833 --> 00:01:14,083
Interviewer: We know that ISIS used specific titles
for positions

14
00:01:14,125 --> 00:01:21,666
Like the Emir, the Governor, and the Sharia judge,
can you tell us about each of their roles?

15
00:01:22,291 --> 00:01:26,208
The Emir, what is his role,
and the Governor and the Sharia judge?

16
00:01:26,250 --> 00:01:32,708
Of course ISIS's titles differ from other organizations,
being ultimately a military organization

17
00:01:32,916 --> 00:01:36,541
They differ from the titles used
by armies and other organizations

18
00:01:36,833 --> 00:01:40,083
We know there are officer ranks and so on,
but they

19
00:01:40,208 --> 00:01:43,666
Had the Emir, the interrogator,
and the Sharia judge

20
00:01:44,125 --> 00:01:48,666
This place functions like a security branch,
let us say an intelligence branch for example

21
00:01:49,916 --> 00:01:57,583
The guards would come, and of course some of them
were decent people and others were not

22
00:01:57,875 --> 00:02:03,416
The person who came to take photographs,
we only saw him once, we can consider him the archive

23
00:02:04,291 --> 00:02:08,166
Those people had no titles
and were considered soldiers of the caliphate

24
00:02:09,125 --> 00:02:13,416
The interrogator who conducted interrogations
was also the Emir of Bourj Prison

25
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:20,666
He was different from the security Emir,
and the judge reviews the prisoner's file

26
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:24,875
He summons the prisoner and tells him,
you did such-and-such, and this is your sentence

27
00:02:25,083 --> 00:02:31,125
This is what you have done, and of course
that happens after you have confessed and he tells you everything

28
00:02:31,333 --> 00:02:35,166
He tells you, you did such-and-such,
and this is your sentence, case closed

29
00:02:35,708 --> 00:02:40,666
Some prisoners received their sentences
in their cells, which I learned later

30
00:02:41,041 --> 00:02:45,166
They hand it to them on a paper that says,
so-and-so, come, this is your sentence

31
00:02:45,416 --> 00:02:52,000
Or, so-and-so, come, perform <i>wudu</i> [ablution],
prepare yourself, perform ablution and prepare yourself means your life is over

32
00:02:53,333 --> 00:03:00,416
Interviewer: There were some ISIS members
who were called foreign fighters

33
00:03:00,875 --> 00:03:07,833
Interviewer: Were there foreign fighters here
in the prison? And how did you communicate with them if so?

34
00:03:08,625 --> 00:03:13,166
The members who were of foreign nationalities,
not Syrian

35
00:03:14,375 --> 00:03:20,625
A Saudi one time, I recognized him
by his accent, a Saudi person

36
00:03:20,791 --> 00:03:27,541
He came in here and was talking, and I recognized
his accent, being alone I paid attention to every sound

37
00:03:28,666 --> 00:03:33,791
Another time, a foreigner appeared,
and there were Iraqis who would come in

38
00:03:34,083 --> 00:03:40,416
But most of them were locals from the area,
from Tabqa or its countryside, they were the ones interrogating us

39
00:03:42,458 --> 00:03:47,416
Interviewer: How did you communicate
with people of foreign nationalities?

40
00:03:47,458 --> 00:03:52,041
The foreign members did not communicate
with us directly

41
00:03:52,541 --> 00:03:58,875
Except the judge who was Saudi, but I was not brought
before him, in the end I was brought before an Iraqi Sharia judge

42
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:03,166
They said, this is the Sharia judge or the sheikh,
and they warned us about speaking in the sheikh's presence

43
00:04:03,208 --> 00:04:08,166
They coached us on how to behave before the sheikh,
saying, do not move, and when we tell you to stand, you stand

44
00:04:08,875 --> 00:04:15,333
We had no contact with foreigners at all,
except in the tunnel there was a foreigner, obvious from his accent, who only beat people

45
00:04:16,375 --> 00:04:20,583
His Arabic was broken,
so we knew he was a foreigner

46
00:04:20,750 --> 00:04:24,625
We do not know his nationality,
because everyone was masked

47
00:04:24,791 --> 00:04:30,625
Possibly Uzbeks, who are recognizable by their facial
features, or Afghans, or people from those countries
